Sure! Below is a complete HTML code for a simple web app that showcases a clock that updates every second, simulating 10 seconds for every real second. It features a simplistic view of skyscrapers with yellow and black windows.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>City Skyscrapers Clock</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #87CEFA; /* Sky color */
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        .clock {
            font-size: 2em;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            color: #333;
        }

        .city {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-around;
            width: 100%;
            height: 200px;
            position: relative;
            overflow: hidden;
        }

        .skyscraper {
            width: 60px;
            height: 100%;
            background-color: #808080; /* Grey color for buildings */
            position: relative;
            margin: 0 2px;
        }

        .window {
            width: 80%;
            height: 10px;
            position: absolute;
            background-color: black;
            left: 10%;
            animation: blink 1s infinite;
        }

        @keyframes blink {
            0%, 100% {
                background-color: black;
            }
            50% {
                background-color: yellow;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="clock" id="clock">Time: 0</div>
    <div class="city">
        <div class="skyscraper" style="height: 80%;">
            <div class="window" style="top: 10%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 30%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 50%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 70%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 90%;"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="skyscraper" style="height: 90%;">
            <div class="window" style="top: 10%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 25%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 45%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 55%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 75%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 85%;"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="skyscraper" style="height: 70%;">
            <div class="window" style="top: 20%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 40%;"></div>
            <div class="window" style="top: 60%;"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        let simulatedTime = 0;
        const clockElement = document.getElementById('clock');

        function updateClock() {
            simulatedTime += 1; // Increase simulated time by 1 sec
            clockElement.textContent = `Time: ${Math.floor(simulatedTime / 10)}`; // Display the time in seconds
        }

        setInterval(updateClock, 100); // Update every 100 ms (10 real seconds = 1000 ms)
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- The HTML features a clock displaying the simulated time.
- The `city` section features multiple `skyscraper` divs, each containing `window` divs. The windows blink between yellow and black, simulating lights inside the buildings.
- The CSS styles the clock, the sky, the skyscrapers, and the windows.
- The JavaScript updates the simulated time by incrementing it every 100 milliseconds (10 times a second), and updates the display accordingly.
